column168: On March 6, 2017, XPO Logistics (UDV Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3264, Sure Klean 600, 8, II (PRO#555650546) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were loading a trailer (CTRQ37453), when terminal personnel discovered (1) 55 gallon poly drum to be leaking inside of the trailer. The caller indicated that the drum appeared to be damaged by a broken pallet.  The caller indicated that approximately all 55 gallons has been released to the trailer floor.Contractor advised that they had arrived on site and assessed the area. It appears as if the drum had been punctured by a fork lift causing the release of approximately 30 gallons of material to the dock, trailer and parking lot. Approximately 15 gallons of which impacted the parking lot.  The contractor cleaned the parking area and trailer with a sodium bicarbonate solution and granular absorbents. Any impacted pallets were neutralized and broken down as waste. The contractor generated (3) 55 gallon poly and (1) 30 gallon poly drum of neutralized debris and absorbents which have been labeled as non hazardous waste. The damaged drum was overpacked into a 95 gallon poly drum and labeled as hazardous waste.

column168: At 1123 hours, a CSX Hazardous Materials Manager was notified by FRA inspector, Scott Hoose that he, "observed loaded hazmat tank car UTLX 951031, containing UN 1075, Liquefied Petroleum Gas, 2.1, emitting a strong product vapor from the service equipment."  The car was isolated and the Shipper Sheena Brista P#403-298-2131, Plains Midstream Canada was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2017030300097.  A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro, was dispatched to the scene.  Upon inspection it was determined the release was coming from the vapor line plugs.  They removed the plugs and observed a build up of teflon tape.  To secure the car Sunpro cleaned the plugs, re-applied teflon tape, then tightened the plugs tool tight.      Cause Code - 385 at 5 NAR points  NARRI - 5 (5 + 5 + 0) x (2 + 0) = 100

column168: On 03/03/17 at 2325 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at CSXT Gentilly Yard, New Orleans, LA, that tank car UTLX670515, a loaded tank car of ISOPROPENYLBENZENE, had product coming from the manway area. United States Environmental Services (USES/ CSX Hazmat Contractor) was dispatched to the scene. USES arrived onsite and confirmed product released from the manway onto the sides of the car. USES discovered that the 4 of 6 manway securement bolts were less than tool tight and unsecured. The shipper, Advansix Inc (LARRY D. BUFFEY JR, (989) 244-6115) was notified. USES secured the manway and installed a seal. The car was released. No special switching moves were required.      NAR Code: 200 (5 pts) Manway Bolts/ Nuts less than tool tight    5(3+1+0) x (2+0) = 40 NARRI      New Orleans, LA – 03/03/2017 – UTLX670515 – ISOPROPENYLBENZENE

column168: ASOX 296043 was reported to have an odor coming from it in the Roseville inbound yard, track 205. The bottom outlet valve was found to be leaking product at the BOV flange at a rate of one drip per minute.     3 out of 8 flange bolts had up to 1/4 inch of shank exposed, and were rusted in place. The other 5 flange bolts were less then tool tight. All 8 bolts were tightened and the leak at the BOV flange stopped.     Then it was noticed that the BOV nozzle flange was leaking product. 4 out of 4 nozzle flange bolts were less then tool tight. They were tightened and the leak stopped. This is an indicator that the bottom outlet is defective and leaking.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: The material had been re-packaged from non-shippable IBC's at the customers location. The procedure required the material be loaded fro the bottom, through the valve. Prior to securing the valve caps, a small amount of product residue was left in the valve body and trapped when the dust caps were applied. During transport, 4 of the IBC's began to leak this residue past the dust caps. The driver noticed the release while trans-loading the material to another trailer. The driver immediately segregated the material, placing it in a containment area. Absorbents were deployed under the suspect valves. A representative of the shipper arrived in the a.m. of 3/17/17 to evaluate and remediate the situation. The shippers representative, after donning proper PPE wiped out the valve bodies and re-applied the dust caps with the proper torque. The IBC's will be monitored for any further release and if none exist, will be shipped to their original destination. Clean up material was collected and disposed of properly.
column169: Containers which require bottom loading will be carefully inspected for residue in the valve bodies. Proper torque will be applied to the cap closure on all valves going forward.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: On 03/02/17, JBHU 237175 was reported LEAKING upon deramp at BNSF Phoenix. The waybill listed the cargo as Hazardous Material (UN1263  PAINT). In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit. JB Hunt was contacted and immediately dispatched Kary  Environmental Services for the required response and remediation. the attached Cargo Report contains photos and seal change information.  Upon arrival, Kary Environmental observed a thick, white substance coming from the container  above the tires. The majority of the product was dry.  However, some product was slowly dripping onto the tires. The interior inspection revealed palletized units containing (5) gallon pails of Paint/Primer  (Hazardous Flammable Liquid / UN1263). All cargo consisted of this same product and was stretch wrapped to the pallets. The palletized units were  stowed in two rows and one layer in height, with the pails stacked (3) high. The source of the leak was identified on the rear pallet at the left sidewall. Two  of the pails stowed at the upper layer, had one small hole each; slowly leaking Paint/Primer. It appears the holes were created as the pails rubbed  against the A Track anchor on the container sidewall.  Securement consisted of Air Bags at the rear and midpoint. Additional rear securement included upright pallets at each stack, secured with wood floor  blocking and a lumber load bar. Kary Environmental completed the clean up and remediation. Approximately (2) gallons (total), leaked from the two pails.  The leaking pails were overpacked and transported to Kary Environmental. The unit was released for outage.  Important Information
column169: Inspect all loads secured prior to offering for transportation to ensure packages will not be compromised during transport by each other or foreign objects.

column168: At 1225 ERTS received a call from Danny Garcia of XPO Logistics - UVC to report a spill. It was reported that at 1210 hours terminal personnel discovered (1) 1.32 gallon container of Hydrogen Peroxide & Peroxyacetic Acid Mixture damaged resulting in the release of all its contents to the trailer floor of trailer #3114708 due to a possible nail puncture (improper loading  by previous terminal UKC). Prior to contacting ERTS terminal personnel cleaned the release by placing spill absorbents on the impacted area and placing the damaged container into a plastic liner and into a steel drum. ERTS instructed the caller to place the damaged plastic liner into a poly drum, caller noted they only have 55 gallon poly drums available and will place it into a poly drum. ERTS also instructed the caller to place baking soda on the impacted area to bring the pH of the product up to 7.0. No storm drains, waterways, or soils were impacted by this release; due to the release of the hazardous product outside of its original container size, ERTS contacted CEMA and received report #17-2194 from Tim at 1238; ERTS contacted Ventura County CUPA to report the spill but was not issued a report number and was told they will contact me back.

column168: TRACTOR WAS TRAVELING ON I-285 WHEN THE LEFT DRIVE TIRE EXPLODED. DRIVER TRIED TO CONTROL THE VEHICLE AS MUCH AS HE COULD, AS HE WENT ACROSS THE HIGHWAY AND HIT THE JERSEY WALL, WHERE HIS TRUCK AND TRAILER ALMOST TIPPED OVER. TRUCK AND TRAILER RESTED ON THE CONCRETE WALL LEANING TO THE RIGHT. TOTES SHIFTED TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND PILED UP ON TOP OF EACH OTHER, WHICH CAUSED SOME OF THEM TO GET CRUSHED AND PUNCTURED. REMTECH WERE CALLED AT THE SCENE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND MOVE THE LOAD TO A DIFFERENT LOCATION. REMTECH TRANSFERRED THE CORROSIVE LIQUID INTO NEW CLEAN TOTES AND THEN TRANSPORTED THEM TO A DIFFERENT LOCATION. ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT 16:00 ON FRIDAY, MARCH 3RD AND THE CLEANING PROCESS CONTINUED UTIL 1:30 AM ON SUNDAY MARCH 4TH. THE PRODUCT DID RELEASE FROM THE TRAILER INTO THE ROADWAY SECTION BEING CONSTRUCTED (CRUSHER RUN BASE). THAT WAS ALL THAT WAS IMPACTED WAS THE CRUSHER RUN BASE MATERIAL.

column168: On 03/19/2017, at 1839 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Hamlet Yard discovered PROX 75276, a loaded tank car of Ethylene Glycol, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Rick Ferguson (Shell) was notified. (CHEMTREC Report #2017-0319-00036 ). SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the sample port was open and the sample port cap was off. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Rick Ferguson Ph#832-712-9770. Contractor personnel (fixed the problem) and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 513 Sample Line Valve Open  NARRI:5(5+1+0)x(2+0)=60

column168: ROSS EXPRESS DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY (SMALL BATTERY) TO A CUSTOMER/RESIDENTIAL AND WHEN THE DRIVER MOVED THE BATTERY OUT OF THE BOX THE SHIPPER HAD TRANSPORTED THE BATTERY IN FROM THE TRAILER TO THE CUSTOMER’S PORCH, HE NOTICED THE BATTERY HAD BEEN LEAKING. THE DRIVER PLACED THE BATTERY BACK IN THE BOX IN THE TRAILER AND CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR @ 9AM ON 3/22/17 TO REPORT THE HM INCIDENT. THE SUPERVISOR REVIEWED THE HM BOL AGAINST THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK GUIDE PAGE 154, FOR CORROSIVE MATERIAL AND HOW TO HANDLE THE LEAKING PRODUCT PROPERLY. HE ADVISED THE DRIVER TO REPLACE HIS CLOTHES THAT THE ACID HAD SPILLED ON, CLEAN HIS WOODEN PALLET AS RECOMMENDED AND TO WASH HIS HANDS EXTENSIVELY DUE TO HIS HANDLING OF THE BATTERY. THE DRIVER WENT TO A LOCAL STORE AND PURCHASED PRODUCTS TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID THAT HAD LEAKED FROM THE BATTERY. HE WAS ASKED IF HE NEEDED MEDICAL ATTENTION DUE TO BEING EXPOSED TO THE LEAKING BATTERY AND HE WOULD BE ALLOWED TO GET ANY TREATMENT IF THE DRIVER THOUGHT IT WAS NECESSARY. THE DRIVER REFUSED MEDICAL ATTENTION CLAIMING THERE WAS NO EXPOSURE ISSUES. OUR DRIVER WAS CHECKED ON SEVERAL TIMES DURING HIS DAY TO MAKE SURE HE WAS OKAY TO CONTINUE OR NOT AND AGAIN HE MADE CLAIMS HE WAS ALRIGHT. THE BATTERY WAS PLACED IN CONTAINMENT PACKAGE AND WAS SENT BACK TO SHIPPER FOR DISPOSAL IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A PACKAGE FAILURE AT THE SHIPPER LEVEL. THE BATTERY HAD NO OBVIOUS VISUAL/DETECTABLE DAMAGE FROM SHIPPING THE BATTERY.
column169: CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE THEM AWARE OF THE PACKAGE FAILURE AND THE RETURN OF THE PACKAGE FOR THEM TO REVIEW AND DISPOSE OF PROPERLY. NOTIFIED – DAVID ABBATINOZZI – DISTRIBUTION CENTER SUPERVISOR @ MILTON CAT MILFORD, MA @ 508 634 5828

column168: On Saturday March 19 at 0920 hours an IMTT Water Treatment Operator was over at 5th Street and noticed oil coming from the bleeder pot of Pump 9. The Water Treatment Operator immediately investigated and shut a valve going to the bleeder pot and notified the IMTT Operations Supervisor. IMTT was in the process of loading a ship on Pier A from Tank 4006 and bypassing Pump 9 to flush the line after just coming back into service. The IMTT Operations Supervisor called the IMTT Operations Manager to inform him of the situation. The IMTT Operations Manager responded to the area to start investigating and oversee the clean up process.  It is unknown at this time who opened the valve into the bleeder pot. The IMTT Operations Manager and Assistant Manager have spoken to the Operations Supervisor whom oversaw the work on Saturday to get the line back into service.  US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO) was called to perform the cleanup operations which were completed by the end of the day. The NRC and the USCG were both notified of the incident due to PHMSA Regulations. The USCG sent a crew of 4 to investigate and they were satisified with our efforts to clean up.
column169: IMTT conducted an investigation to determine why the bleeder valve was left open.  All IMTT personnel and contractors involved were interviewed and to date the person who opened the valve has not been identified.

column168: Paint related material from a HHW collection facility was packaged in a cubic yard box with a liner. column168: At approximately 0120 hrs. the Brewster Yard switch crew heard tank car PROX 39537 leaking from on top of the car. I came out to investigate and when I was next to the car with the window up on my vehicle, I could hear the car hissing from up on top.  I found that the vapor valve was leaking through the valve plug caused by a loose valve handle.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I then tightened the loose valve plug and then released the car for service.

column168: On March 10, 2017 at approximately 19:30 hours the Q58309 moving south approaching the north end of Resaca, GA derailed 9 cars- one of which was a UTLX 680675, tank car, residue: last contained Ethanol.  The shipper, Sun Products Corp, was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2017-0310-00213).  Marion Environmental (MEI), a CSX response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to assess the car.  MEI found the car actively releasing product vapors upon their arrival.  MEI reported that during the derailment the tank cars protective housing sustained an impact which caused the pressure plate bolts to fail.  This allowed vapor to release from between the cars pressure plate and tank shell nozzle.  Because tank car repair cost were estimated to exceed the value of the car; the car was set over from the tracks and subsequently cleaned and purged on site in preparation to dismantling.      Per Umler this is a DOT 117J100W, the system will not allow me to enter the correct car type code.

column168: At 0150 hrs., the WLE Brewster Yard Switch Crew head car PROX 39537 exhausting air from on top of the car.  They called the Brewster Yardmaster who in turn contacted myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE. I came out to investigate and when I approached the car, I could hear gas exhausting from the top of the car with the windows up on my vehicle.  I found that the vapor valve on the car has a loose valve handle causing the valve to leak through the valve plug which I also found to be loose.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped and then I tightened the valve plug.  I then released the car for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV), FOR NATX 29071 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING OUTBOUND INSPECTION FROM THE CP NAHANT YARD ON 3-7-17 AT APPROXIMATELY 22:00. A QULIFED ER CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO SITE, SUBSEQUENTLY FINDING THAT THE BOV CAP WAS LOOSE. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. APPROXIMATELY LESS THAN 1 PINT OF MATERIAL WAS BELIEVED TO BE LOST, BASED UPON THE FREQUENCY OF DRIP FROM THE CAP. ON 3-10-17, DURING SUBSEQUENT OUTBOUND INSPECTION, THE BOV WAS FOUND TO BE WEEPING AROUND THE UPPER THREADS OF THE VALVE NIPPLE. THE VALVE WAS THEN CONSIDERED TO BE NON-FIELD REPAIRABLE, AND THE CAR WAS BAD-ORDERED. ON 3-11-17, THE CHEMCIAL WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE NATX 29071 TO A IDENTIFIED RECEIVING CAR, ECUX 461204. THE BAD-ORDER CAR WAS THEN CLEANED, PURGE AND MADE READY FROM TRANSPORTATION TO A REPAIR SHIP USING ON OTMA 3 SUBMITTED MOVEMENT.
column169: Continued emphasis with Offerers/Shippers to conduct thorough tank car inspections prior to movement will reduce valve failures in the field.

column168: ENVIROSERVE NOTICED A DISCREPANCY IN THE NUMBER OF CONTAINERS THAT WERE PICKED UP AT DOMINION AFTER THE SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED AT ENVIROSERVES’S CLEVELAND, OH TERMINAL. THE EXTRA CONTAINER WAS LABELED IDENTICALLY TO, AND LOOKED IDENTICAL TO, SEVERAL “SUPERSACKS” OF NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE. ENVIROSERVE CONTACTED DOMINION WITH THIS INFORMATION.  AFTER INVESTIGATING, DOMINION DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER HELD FRIABLE ASBESTOS CONTAINING MATERIAL AND INFORMED ENVIROSERVE. ENVIROSERVE CONFIRMED THAT THE EXTRA CONTAINER WAS MIS-LABELED AND WAS NOT A DOT COMPLIANT SHIPPING CONTAINER FOR THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. ENVIROSERVE REPACKED THE WASTE MATERIAL INTO A DOUBLE LINED (6 MIL POLY) CUBIC YARD BOX WITH THE SPECIFICATION OF UN11G/X/0915/USA/+AA6789/1882/997 AND SHIPPED IT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
column169: DOMINION OFFERED ENVIROSERVE AND UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FOR TRANSPORTATION. ENVIROSERVE WILL REMAIN DILIGENT IN INQUIRING ABOUT THE CONTENTS OF CONTAINERS, AND ALSO TO ENSURE THAT COUNTING OF CONTAINERS IS ACCURATE. DOMINION HAS INFORMED ENVIROSERVE THAT THEY INTENT TO PERFORM A ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS OF THIS INCIDENT. OUTCOMES FROM THIS WILL INCLUDE: PERSONNEL AWARENESS TRAINING AS TO FACILITY COMPONENTS WHICH MAY CONTAIN ASBESTOS; PERSONNEL TRAINING ON LABELING AND CONTAINERIZATION OF FRIABLE ASBESTOS CONTAINING MATERIAL; AND REINFORCING ATTENTION TO DETAIL ON CONTAINER COUNT WHEN OFFERING SHIPMENTS FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: AMERIGAS EMPLOYEE ARRIVED AT HIS TENTH STOP OF THE DAY LOCATED AT 841 W. SAMPLE ROAD IN DEERFIELD BEACH, FL WHERE HE WAS ASSIGNED TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO TWO (02) DOT-420# CYLINDERS. UPON ARRIVAL DELIVERY REPRESENTATIVE IDENTIFIED THAT EACH TANK CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 38% AND HE PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE FIXED MAXIMUM LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE (FMLLG) IN ORDER TO COMMENCE THE FILLING PROCESS. WHEN IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT ONLY VAPOR WAS EMITTING FROM THE FMLLG THE DELIVERY HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THE REGO 7647SC FILLER VALVE AND THE VEHICLE PTO WAS ACTIVATED USING THE RF-ESD REMOTE. AFTER DELIVERING 55 GALLONS OF PROPANE TO CYLINDER 6343414 LIQUID BEGAN TO EMIT FROM THE FMLLG SIGNIFYING THAT THE CYLINDER WAS FULL. THE DELIVERY REPRESENTATIVE CLOSED THE HOSE END VALVE AND BEGAN TO DISCONNECT THE CYLINDER FILLER VALVE.  ONCE LOOSENED FROM THE FILLER VALVE A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID RELEASED FROM THE WEEP HOLE CONSTRUCTED IN THE THREADED CONNECTION. ONCE THE LIQUID STOPPED EMITTING THE HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED AND A SUBSTANTIAL AMOUNT OF PROPANE VAPOR WAS RELEASED FROM THE VALVE THAT FAILED TO PROPERLY RE-CLOSED THROUGH THE VALVES INTEGRATED DOUBLE BACK CHECK. THE RELEASING VAPOR MIGRATED TO A SOURCE OF IGNITION ALMOST IMMEDIATELY AND IGNITED.   THE BURNING PROPANE VAPOR IMPACTED THE ADJACENT TANK CAUSING THE RELIEF VALVE TO ACTIVATE, AS WELL AS IGNITING THE ADJACENT STRUCTURE. THE DELIVERY REPRESENTATIVE EXPERIENCED BURNS FROM THE FLASH FIRE, BUT WAS ABLE TO ACTIVATE THE TRUCK ESV SYSTEM USING THE KILL SWITCH ON THE RF-ESD REMOTE. THE BUILDING OCCUPANTS WERE EVACUATED AND 9-1-1 WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE ENSUING FIRE.
column169: THE CONTAINER APPURTENANCE WHICH WAS DETERMINED TO FAIL RESULTING IN THE RELEASE IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION AND WE ARE UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY INSIGHT WITH REGARD TO PREVENTION OF RECURRENCE AT THIS TIME.

column168: PLAINS UNIT WAS HEADING WEST ON HWY 23 APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE EAST OF WATFORD CITY IN CV #9899 PULLING PUP TRAILER #1358, WHEN THE EE NOTICED AN OV APPROXIMATELY ½ MILE AHEAD HAD HIS RIGHT TURN SIGNAL ON AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING A RIGHT HAND TURN ONTO 125TH AVE HEADING NORTH, INSTEAD THE OTHER VEHICLE BLOCKED THE INTERSECTION OF 125TH AVE TO EXECUTE A U-TURN BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY. AS THE PLAINS UNIT APPROACHED THE OTHER VEHICLE PROCEEDED TO PULL OUT ONTO THE HIGHWAY IMPACTING PLAINS UNIT #9899 ON THE REAR PASSENGER SIDE, CAUSING IT TO ROLLOVER ALONG WITH THE PUP TRAILER #1358 ONTO IT PASSENGER SIDE IN THE HIGHWAY. THE CV SLID APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET DOWN THE HWY COMING TO A STOP ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF HWY 23. THE PLAINS EMPLOYEE WAS ABLE TO FORCEFULLY KICK THE FRONT WINDOW OUT ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF CV 9899 TO ESCAPE THE CAB. LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE AT THE SCENE AND HAD THE DRIVERS OF BOTH VEHICLES TRANSPORTED TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL OUT OF CAUTION VIA AMBULANCE.  PLAINS EMPLOYEE WAS GIVEN A FULL RELEASE TO RETURN TO WORK WITHOUT RESTRICTIONS. APPROXIMATELY 2.5 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL AND 2.5 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FROM THE FULE TANK WERE RELEASED DURING THE INCIDENT, NO WATER WAYS WERE AFFECTED AND THE RELEASE WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THERE WAS DAMAGE TO THE BODY AND PUP TRAILER BUT NONE OF THE CONTENTS WERE RELEASED.

column168: On March 25, 2017, at 2042 hours, a Transportation Manager at the CSXT Parsons Terminal, Columbus, Ohio reported that UTLX 200889, a loaded tank car of UN1307, Xylenes was leaking from the top of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper Citgo,  were notified via Chemtrec, report # 2017-03-25-00104.Environmental Management Specialists (EMS), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the Terminal and found a slow active release from the Bread Box area on top of the tank car.    The breadbox was opened and the release was emanating from the liquid line valve area. In an effort to stop the active release the internal pressure was relieved by opening the vapor line valve. The release stopped once the internal pressure was relieved and the valve was inspected. The liquid line plug was removed and the internal valve was inspected for proper working condition. The ball valve opened and closed with no visual defects. The securement plug was inspected and all threads appeared in proper condition. The securement plug was re-secured with thread sealant applied to the threads. No root cause for the release was determined at that time. The Shipper, Citgo, Darnell Parker (630) 257-4252 was notified of the conditions found.    CSX Hazmat decided to return to the tank car on Monday, March 27, 2017 to perform a further inspection. Nitrogen was added to the tank car to increase the internal pressure and inspect the tank car for the root cause of the release. Upon an increase of internal pressure it was discovered that product was escaping around the internal ball valve and the gasket.     The Shipper, Citgo, Darnell Parker (630) 257-4252 was notified of the conditions found and both CSX and Citgo decided the liquid line valve needed to be replaced as soon as possible to avoid any additional product release. Sunpro, a CSXT response contractor and AAR certified mobile repair facility was contacted and advised they had an exact new replacement valve. Sunpro was mobilized to the Terminal to replace the valve and perform a field bubble leak test to re-qualify the tank car for transportation.    NARRI: 2x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 32  Cause code: 693

column168: On March 27, 2017 during unloading operations, terminal discovered a (1) 55-gallon poly drum containing UN2491 pH Balancer "PI-104" that had tipped over and leaked from the lid. Approximately 10-gallons released to the trailer floor on trailer #3132904. No waterways, soils, and drains were reported to have been impacted. A contractor was dispatched who contained, cleaned, and neutralized the release by utilizing granular absorbents and a citric acid solution. All generated waste and salvaged material was containerized and staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: during offloading operations, it was discovered that approximately 8 liquid ounces of a UN2031 Nitric Acid was released (and confined) to the top rim of a 55 gallon metal drum resulting from a loose drum cap. The liquid product was reported to be bubbling and reacting with the metal drum. An environmental contractor was dispatched and transferred the product into a poly drum. A commercial branded neutralizer was applied the metal drum and it was over packed. The poly salvage drum and over packed metal drum were staged on site for the terminal to manage disposition

On March 30, 2017, XPO Logistics (LGT Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3082, 2-4,D LV6, 9, III (PRO#549455966) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were loading a trailer (3175415) when terminal personnel discovered (1) 275 gallon poly tote was cracked. Approximately 1 gallon of product has been released to the trailer floor. Contractor indicated that approximately 1 gallon of product has been released to the trailer floor along with a 4' x 4' area of concrete area beneath the trailer. Contractor will remove some freight from the trailer before they being to transfer the tote.Contractor used absorbent materials to clean the release. Contractor transferred the product into a new 275 gallon poly tote for salvage material. Contractor generated (2) 55 gallon poly drums of impacted absorbent materials, debris, PPE and the cut up tote for waste to be staged on site for XPO to manage disposition.

One 5 gallon poly jug containing UN3264 Corrosive Liquid was discovered on the dock with a defective cap releasing approximately 1 ounce of material. Terminal personnel performed cleanup. The damaged jug was placed into a salvage drum which was staged onsite pending disposition. No drains, soils, or waterways were impacted.

On 03/28/17 at 1225 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at CSXT Gentilly Yard, New Orleans, LA, that tank car UTLX213481, a residue tank car of Butanols, had vapor venting from the vacuum relief device.  United States Environmental Services (USES/ CSX Hazmat Contractor) was dispatched to the scene.  USES arrived onsite and confirmed product released from the vacuum relief valve.  USES discovered that protective housing was in the open position, vapor line plug was not installed, and the vacuum relief valve was venting product vapors. The shipper, Eastman Chemical / C/o Taminco (Julie Brown 423-361-6420) was notified.  ResCar responded at the direction of the shipper and replaced the vacuum relief valve.  USES secured the protective housing and vapor line plug.  The shipper applied for an OTMA.  The car was released.  No special switching moves were required.        NAR Code: 466 (5 pts) Vacuum Relief Valve- valve body other     2(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 20 NARRI         New Orleans, LA – 03/28/2017 – UTLX213481 – BUTANOLS

column168: On March 31, 2017,  XPO Logistics (URE Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3378, Green Clean PRO Broad Spectrum Algaecide/Fungicide Oxidizer, 5.1, II (PRO#836051930) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (4254124) from a city pickup, when terminal personnel discovered (1) 50 pound poly bag to be forked. Approximately 5 pounds of product was released to the trailer floor. Following a review of the incident and the reported material involved, ERTS has obtained and reviewed the MSDS with the caller. The terminal personnel stated that they are capable, confident and able to clean the release and will wear the provided PPE and over pack the damaged freight into a 10 gallon poly drum in OS & D.

On March 31, 2017 t was reported that approximately 2 lbs of UN3260 "Oxone PS-16" released from a 50 lb. paper bag that appeared to be torn by adjacent freight during loading. The release impacted the trailer floor. A contractor was dispatched who contained and cleaned the release. The sweepings and damaged bag was overpacked and staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

On March, 22, 2017, Superior Carriers (Travel Order # 50173) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous,  UN1993, Ethyl Acetoacetate, 3, III release. According to the caller, the driver of tractor (5881) 307/407 tanker trailer (1610) went to do his walk around and noticed that there was a large wet area underneath the tanker. It appears that the under belly of the tanker is leaking.An Environmental Contractor was dispatched and indicated there appears to be a white silicone like material acting as a gasket for the valve that is leaking. Approximately 3 gallons of product has been released to a 30' x 4' area of pavement. The Contractor has placed containment underneath the valve to collect the release. The contractor indicated that there is a steady drip of product. Contractor set up tanker transfer activities between the damaged tanker and the relief tanker. The Contractor reports the job is complete and the tankers have departed the site. (1) 55 gallon metal drum containing impacted absorbents and debris is being transported off site for disposal.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 1 quart of material had  escaped from the lid that had developed in container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.   IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

When walking through the 10-day temporary waste storage area, facility personnel noticed that a drum was leaking slightly on a concrete surface in our containment area. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and over packed the drum in properly rated salvage drum for continued transportation to the final disposal facility. The small amount of released liquid was cleaned from the facility floor and the location fully remediated using absorbents, spill pads, and rinsing. The clean up generated waste was added to the appropriate waste stream for the facility.     The release was reported to the NJ DEP 4/4/2017 at 11:35am Case # 170404113007 Operator #73.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The release was found to be a result of the poor condition of the drum; this drum should have been over packed before initial transportation. The driver who picked up this drum from the client site will be given retraining on identifying potential drum integrity issues, and the client will be informed that all drums must be in satisfactory structural condition in order to transport.

column168: On 03/29/17 at 1847 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at CSXT Boyles Yard, Tarrant, AL, that tank car NATX76883, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, N.O.S. (Creosote), had liquid releasing from the bottom outlet valve.  United States Environmental Services (USES/ CSX Hazmat Contractor) was dispatched to the scene.  USES arrived onsite and confirmed product released from the bottom outlet valve.  USES and the CSX General Car Foreman discovered that the bottom outlet valve cap was unsecured and the bottom outlet valve operating handle in the partial open position with the BOV operating handle pin not secured. The shipper, Blackwater Midstream (Erika Babb Cell: (504) 441-8295) was notified.  USES secured the BOV, BOV cap, and installed a seal in the BOV operating handle pin.  The car was released.  No special switching moves were required.        NAR Code: 148 (5 pts) Bottom outlet valve cap- less than tool tight/ valve open     5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60 NARRI         Tarrant, AL – 03/29/2017 – NATX76883 – Environmentally Hazardous Substance N.OS. (Creosote)

column25: RIBOST TERMINAL LLC, DBA WORLD OIL TERMINALS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 01:20 HOURS ON MARCH 11, 2017, A RIO EXPRESS CORP. TANKER TRUCK WAS LOADING CRUDE OIL FROM A WORLD OIL TERMINALS (WOT) LOADING RACK. AT THE END OF THE LOADING PROCESS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO ENGAGE THE DRY LOCK PLUNGER AND THEN DISCONNECTED THE TANKER DRY LOCK. THE TRUCK HEADER PLUNGER FAILED TO FULLY CLOSE AND CONSEQUENTLY ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO CONCRETE WITHIN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE DRIVER RESPONDED BY CLOSING THE BUTTERFLY VALVE UNDER THE TANK COMPARTMENT AND STOPPED THE FLOW. APPROXIMATELY 60-70 GALLONS OF CRUDE OIL SPILLED ONTO CONCRETE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IMMEDIATELY WITHIN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AND CLEANED WITHIN 2 HOURS OF THE INCIDENT. NO INJURIES WERE RECORDED AND NO WATERWAYS OR LAND WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE.  IN RESPONSE TO THE SPILL, WORLD OIL TERMINAL OPERATIONS TEAM IMMEDIATELY STOPPED TRUCK/VEHICLE TRAFFIC IN THE AREA. THE LOADING PROCESS OF THE RACK WAS STOPPED UNTIL CLEAN-UP AND VERIFICATION OF TRUCK HEADER PLUNGER WAS COMPLETED.
column169: THE TRAILER WAS POSTPONED FROM OPERATIONS UNTIL A FULL MECHANICAL VERIFICATION WAS COMPLETED. SINCE THE INCIDENT, THE API LOAD/UNLOAD HEAD HAS BEEN REPLACED, OPERATING PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN AMENDED WITH SECONDARY PRECAUTIONS AND REVIEWED WITH RIO EXPRESS DRIVERS.

column168: On March, 30, 2017,  XPO Logistics (LDA Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1942, Ammonium Nitrate, 5.1, III (PRO#808716020) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (3174221) from the NBM Terminal, when (1) 2000 pound supersack was discovered to be damaged due to improper loading. Approximately 20 pounds of product has been released to the trailer floor. Contractor transferred the product into a new supersack revealing approximately 80 pounds of product released. Contractor transferred the remaining product for salvage material and the spill product was placed into (1) 55 gallon drum for waste.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On March 31, 2017, XPO Logistics (UBY Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN2794, Battery Acid, 8 (PRO#903613594) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (IWXT5139) from the XCW Terminal, when (1) 1500 pound battery was discovered to be tipped over and punctured. Approximately 10 gallons of product was released to the trailer floor. Contractor indicated that the battery has lost all its content. The contractor indicated that the release has spread throughout the trailer and out the nose of the trailer to (2) 4' in diameter areas of concrete beneath the trailer. Contractor indicated that approximately 5 gallons of product has been lost. Contractor is using a caustic soda solution to neutralize the release. Contractor has wrapped the battery in poly and has labeled the battery as salvage. The product itself leaked out of the vent caps. Contractor advised all cleanup actions are complete at this time. They generated 1-55 gallon poly drum of neutralizer and spent absorbents.

I RETURNED ALL CONTENTS IN ORIGINAL PACKAGING AS BEST AS POSSIBLE, PLACED INTO A GREEN DMP BAG AND IT SHALL BE AWAITING INSPECTION IN THE DMP SHED. column168: A trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  The rear doors were opened to inspect the load and a drum was found to be leaking.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum had been pierced by a screw which was used to install a placard holder to the outside of the trailer after the trailer was loaded.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with the absorbents and cleaning compound used to clean the inside of the trailer.  The load was then accepted into the intended waste disposal facility without further incident

column25: Merichem Co. (s/b - Kinder Morgan Liquid Terminals LLC)
column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At approximately 10:37 on 03/09/2017, the GAMX 6460 was found leaking by BNSF yard personnel to be emanating a strong odor.  The immediate area was isolated and operations in the area were suspended until BNSF Hazmat Responders inspected the car.  Two Sodium Bisulfite cars were inspected and the GAMX 6460 was identified as the leaking car by use of a PID.  The leak was observed as coming from the manway cover area.  Responders inspected the manway cover and found 3 swing bolts less than tool tight.  The manway gasket was replaced with a nozzle gasket and the closure was re-secured.  The repair was successful in mitigating the slight vapor release.  There was no release of liquid to the car or ground and released vapors quickly dissipated.
column169: Follow up has occurred with Merichem to investigate loading and securement procedures.  All closures on tank cars should be tool tightened and gaskets should be inspected to ensure they are adequate so that no identifiable release occurs in transportation.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: At approximately 18:25 on 03/09/2017, the GBRX 700462 was found leaking by yard personnel in the Barstow Railyard.  The car was observed to have fresh residue on the top of the car near the manway.  BNSF Hazmat Responders inspected the car and manway closure, it was determined that the manway was missing the gasket.  Responders installed a new manway nozzle gasket and cleaned the residue from the tank car shell.  The manway was re-secured and car released to continue in transportation to destination.  No diesel fuel was released to the soil and was confined exclusively to the car body.
column169: Shipper should ensure that all shipments are inspected in accordance with applicable regulations prior to releasing in transportation.  All closures on the car should be a tool tight condition prior to releasing the container into transportation.

column168: Tank Car UTLX 678090 was reported releasing product in the railyard from the manway lid.  The BNSF responder reported leak source was at UTLX 678090's manway lid.  After inspection it was verified that the manway lid safety swing bolt was not properly secured allowing product to be released when UTLX 678090 was moved.  BNSF Railway responder properly secured the manway lid safety swing bolt and and properly tool tightened the manway swing bolts which ended any further release of product. column168: During a train inspection, a BNSF carman noted an odor emitting from GATX 17174. Upon further inspection of the car, a BNSF responder noted that the vapor release was emitting from the manway area close to the manway lid hinge area through air monitoring. The swing bolts were noted as tool-tight.  The responder opened the manway and confirmed that the lid gasket was not sealing properly near the hinge.  A new nozzle gasket was applied and the manway lid closed and sealed by tool-tight swing bolts. The repair was confirmed through complete air monitoring of the manway lid/nozzle gasket interface.
column169: Shipper has the responsibility to confirm that all gaskets are in proper placement and in proper condition to prevent the release of any hazardous materials. Operating procedures need to be reviewed by all personnel to prevent this from reoccurring in the future.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column43: SULFURIC ACID 93% DELIVERED INTO SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE STORAGE TANK RELEASING
column168: UNIVAR ARRIVED AT THE CUMMINS FACILITY ON MARCH 10, 2017 TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF 93% SULFURIC ACID. UNIVAR’S DRIVER CHECKED INTO THE FACILITY’S SECURITY AND WAS DIRECTED TO THE CHEMICAL UNLOADING LOCATION. THE TANK LEVEL WAS VERIFIED AND AT THE DIRECTION OF THE CUMMINS RECEIVER, UNIVAR WAS INSTRUCTED TO HOOK UP TO A FILL PORT CONNECTION. PRE-DELIVERY PAPERWORK WAS COMPLETED THEN THE DRIVER MADE THE NEEDED CONNECTIONS AS INSTRUCTED. THE FILL PORT CONNECTION FOR SULFURIC ACID AND HYPOCHLORITE ARE SIDE BY SIDE, BUT ARE ADEQUATELY MARKED AND EVEN DIFFERENT SIZES TO PREVENT AN ACCIDENTAL CONNECTION. SHORTLY AFTER COMMENCING THE DELIVERY, THE FLOW STOPPED AND UNIVAR’S DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING FLOW. THE UNIVAR DRIVER, ALONG WITH EMPLOYEE OF CUMMINS OPENED A VALVE IN THE PIPING SYSTEM WHICH ALLOWED THE CHARGED SULFURIC ACID LINE TO FLOW INTO THE HYPOCHLORITE TANK.  ONCE THE SULFURIC ACID IN THE PIPING FLOWED INTO THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANK, CHLORINE GAS WAS RELEASED TO ATMOSPHERE AND THE ROOM VIA THE TANK’S VENT PIPES.  UNIVAR’S DRIVER AND OTHER CUMMINS EMPLOYEES EVACUATED FROM THE AREA AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED VIA 911. UNIVAR’S DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE COLUMBUS REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED SHORTLY THEREAFTER.
column169: UNIVAR AND CUMMINS ARE MEETING TO REVIEW APPROPRIATE DELIVERY INFRASTRUCTURE AND PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THE CONNECTIONS TO THE CHEMICAL STORAGE TANKS ARE CORRECTLY DESIGNED, INSTALLED, LABELED, AND OPERATED.

column168: On March 27, 2017 at 07:59 personnel at the CSXT Willard Terminal observed small puffs of vapor from OLNX 715009, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Olin was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2017-03-27-00063. Sunpro, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Willard Terminal. Sunpro found that the fill hole had the three fill hole securement bolts less than completely tool tight. There was a trace amount of hydrochloric acid found beneath the fill hole hinge that verified the point of release. The shipper representative, Rich O'Hara, 716-278-6544 was notified of the situation found. The tank car was wiped down and then released for transportation.    Cause Code: 224  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column25: CARDINAL HEALTH NUCLEAR PHARMACY SERVICES LOCATION 72
column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE NON-SPECIAL FORM, NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: THE CARDINAL HEALTH VEHICLE WAS A 2013 FORD TRANSIT FROM CARDINAL HEALTH’S HUMMELSTOWN NUCLEAR PHARMACY. THE VEHICLE BECAME DISABLED, PARKED ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND DESTROYED BY FIRE DURING TRANSPORT OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL AT APPROXIMATELY 05:00 AM ON MARCH 17, 2017. THE DRIVER HAD NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM UNDER THE ENGINE HOOD WHILE IN TRANSIT APPROACHING THE TOIL BOOTH ON 1-76 WEST AT EXIT 286. THE DRIVE THEN STOPPED IN A SAFE AREA ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO INVESTIGATE. THE VEHICLE BECAME ENGULFED IN FLAMES WHEN THE DRIVER LIFTED THE ENGINE HOOD. THE CARDINAL HEALTH DOT TRAINED DRIVER SUSTAINED NO INJURIES AND IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED 911. DURING THE COURSE OF THE FIRE, 9 PACKAGES CONTAINING RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL COMPLETELY MELTED. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT MINIMAL RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED BECAUSE THEY WERE CONTAINED IN THE MELTED METAL CONTAINERS WITHIN THE VEHICLE. LANCASTER COUNTY HAZMAT DIRECTED THE DENVER FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ALLOW THE VEHICLE TO BURN ITSELF OUT, WHICH LASTED APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS. THE PADEP RADIATION PROTECTION PROGRAM PERFORMED SURVEYS AT THE SCENE AND REPORTED EXPOSURE RATES OF 50 MR/HR AT THE RIGHT REAR OF THE VEHICLE. A SAFE ZONE WAS SET UP BY LANCASTER HAZMAT AT 2 MR/HR. THE RESIDUAL RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL IN THE VEHICLE DECAYED TO BACKGROUND AFTER 3 DAYS. RESIDUAL MATERIAL REMOVED FROM THE ROAD AT THE SCENE, INCLUDING ASH AND METALS IN A PLASTIC CONTAINER, WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HUMMELSTOWN PHARMACY (RAM LICENSE PA-0415) FOR DECAY IN STORAGE. THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO A HAZMAT IMPOUND LOT AND LATER RELEASED BY PADEP.   FIRE/EMS AND POLICE REPORTS HAVE NOT BEEN RECEIVED BY CARDINAL HEALTH FOR THIS INCIDENT YET.
column169: AT THIS TIME, CARDINAL HEALTH IS UNABLE TO DETERMINE AN APPROPRIATE PATH FOR IMPLEMENTING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE OF SUCH AN INCIDENT. THE VEHICLE FIRE WAS UNPREDICTABLE AND POTENTIALLY NON-PREVENTABLE. AT THIS TIME, THE CAUSE OF THE VEHICLE FIRE IS UNKNOWN. THE CARDINAL HEALTH DRIVER FOLLOWED HIS TRAINING AND ENACTED PROPER OPERATING PROCEDURES DURING THE INCIDENT.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, AN AIR PRESSURE MALFUNCTION WAS DETECTED IN VEHICLE. DRIVER PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO PERFORM INSPECTION OF VEHICLE. UPON INSPECTION, A SUBSTANCE WAS DETECTED AT REAR TRAILER DOOR. UPON OPENING, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM ONE 55-GALLON DRUM INSIDE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS RELEASED TO TRAILER FLOOR, WITH LESS THAN ONE GALLON TO ASPHALT DIRECTLY BENEATH TRAILER. FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO AN IMPERVIOUS SURFACE, AND DID NOT MIGRATE TO SURFACE SOILS OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. TRADEBE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES IMMEDIATELY APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE, AND USED ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN TRAILER FLOOR. THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND PLACED BACK ON TRAILER TO BE SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: TRADEBE TRANSPORTATION LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column169: Procedure to load CO2 from a railcar to be revised to allow sufficient clearing of all product from loading hose.

column168: OUR DRIVER EXITED I-20 EAST AND WAS AT THE LIGHT INTERSECTION OF THE EXIT RAMP 131 AND LOOP-250. OUR DRIVER CLAIMED THERE WERE A FEW CARS IN FRONT. AS THE LIGHT TURNED GREEN, OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO FOLLOW TRAFFIC AS HE TURNED LEFT ONTO LOOP-250. OUR DRIVER CLAIMED HE WAS GOING ABOUT 10 MPH AS HE WAS DOING THE TURN.  THE SLOSH EFFECT AT THIS POINT IS WHAT CAUSED THE CARGO TANK TO FLIP ON IT’S RIGHT SIDE. AT THIS POINT, PRODUCT STARTED TO ESCAPE FROM THE VENT PIPING. OUTLET VALVES, INLET VALVES, INTERNAL BELLY VALVE AND ALL OTHER EXTERNAL PIPING AND ATTACHMENTS REMAINED INTACT AND NO OTHER VISIBLE DAMAGE INCURRED. APPROXIMATELY 11,100 LBS. OF NITROGEN ESCAPED, BUT EVAPORATED VERY QUICKLY INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. NO PROPERTY DAMAGED TO THE ROAD OR INJURIES RESULTED FROM THE SPILL, NOR HAZ-MAT WAS RELEASED INTO A WATER WAY OR STREAM. THE NITROGEN SIMPLY EVAPORATED AND NO CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED, OTHER THAN THE DAMAGED VEHICLES. THE CARGO TANK OUTER SHELL GOT SCRAPPED, DAMAGED AND BENT. THERE WAS NO VISIBLE INDICATION THAT THE INNER TANK BROKE OR RUPTURED, BUT WITHOUT CERTAINTY. THE TANK HAS A BOLTED MANHOLE COVER AND AFTER A FEW HOURS AFTER BEING ON ITS SIDE, IT STARTED TO SHOW FROST AROUND THE SEAL ON THE MANHOLE COVE, BUT IT REMAINED INTACT. DUE TO NOT KNOWING THE INTEGRITY OF THE INNER TANK, WE PUMPED THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT WHICH WAS ABOUT 33,300 LBS. OF NITROGEN ONTO A DIFFERENT CARGO TANK TO HAUL AWAY. AFTER THE NITROGEN WAS PUMPED OUT, THE VEHICLES WERE TURNED UPRIGHT AND TOWED AWAY TO OUR YARD. THIS CARGO TANK HAD A LOT OF DAMAGE TO THE OUTER SHELL, IN ADDITION, THERE MAY BE UNKNOWN INNER TANK DAMAGES. THEREFORE, WE HAVE DECIDED TO DISPOSE OF HIS TANK AND PLACED IT OUT OF SERVICE. IT’S NOT SALVAGEABLE, THE DAMAGES AND REPAIRS EXCEED THE VALUE OF THE TANK. I HAVE INCLUDED SOME PICTURES FOR CLARIFICATION.
column169: WE HAVE TAKEN MEASURES TO RE-TRAIN OUR DRIVERS THAT OPERATE CARGO TANK VEHICLES WITH LIQUIDS BY PROVIDING A MORE IN-DEPTH CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE TRAINING. WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED MORE TRAINING VIDEOS, CLASSROOM, AND ON ROAD TRAINING. IN ADDITION, SUPERVISORS WERE RE-INFORMED THAT BEFORE ASSIGNING A DRIVER TO OPERATE A CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE THAT CONTAINS LIQUID, THEY CANNOT DO SO UNTIL PROPERLY RE-TRAINED AND EXPERIENCED AND RECEIVE CLEARANCE FROM OUR DRIVER TRAINER(S). WE BELIEVE THAT THE LACK OF EXPERIENCE IS THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT AND WE HAVE IMPLEMENTED MEASURES TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: During a train inspection product was visible on the side of the car.  Upon inspection it was determined that one manway swing bolt was finger loose and one was less than tool tight, all other bolts were properly secured. The release was directly below these two bolts.  The bolts were properly tightened, the release area on the car was wiped down and the car released back into transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: Tank car TILX 199147 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached an burned. The breach occurred on the A end tank head. It was approx. 1 ft x 1 ft in size. Once the fire was extinguished the remaining product was transferred into frac tanks for disposal.  Tank car TAEX 2893 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. The breach occurred on the B end left side of the tank. It was approx. 2 ft x 1 ft in size. Once the fire was extinguished the remaining product was transferred into a frac tank for disposal.  Tank car CTCX 731997 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. The breach occurred on the A end tank head and was approx. 2 ft x 1 ft in size. Once the fire was extinguished the remaining product was transferred into a frac tank for disposal.  Tank car TAEX 2909 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. The breach was a 10 inch x 10 inch hole on the tank head B end.  Tank car DBUX 301674 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was burned. The fire was put out and remaining product was transferred into a frac tank for disposal.  Tank car TCBX 198194 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. The breach occurred on the A end tank head near the bottom of the car and was approx. 3 ft x 2 ft in size. Once the fire was extinguished the remaining product was transferred into a frac tank for disposal.  Tank car CTCX732108 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. There were 2 breach's that occurred. One on the top of the car which was 24 inches x 24 inches and one on the left side mid tank which was 10 inches x 3 inches. The bottom outlet nozzle was also sheared off. The fire was extinguished and remaining product was transferred into frac tanks for disposal.  Tank car WCHX 30098 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. The car was releasing from the bottom outlet valve. The valve was tightened to stop the release. Once the fire was extinguished the remaining product was transferred into a frac tank for disposal.  Tank car WCHX 30078 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger, IA. As a result of the derailment the car was breached and burned. There were 2  breach's that occurred. One on the right side mid car towards the B end it was approx. 6 ft x 6 ft. The other breach occurred on the left side of the car near the A end. It was approx. 6 ft x 4 ft. in size. Once the fire was extinguished the remaining product was transferred into frac tanks for disposal.  Tank car CTCX 731383 was involved in a derailment near Graettinger

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car UTLX200492 leaking product from the top of the car. THE DRIVER LOADED 2000 GALLONS OF CAUSTIC SODA INTO ONE COMPARTMENT OF A FOUR COMPARTMENT TRAILER. THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE COMPARTMENT WAS LEAKING WHICH CHARGED THE LINE TO THE MINI-BULK PUMP CABINET. THE VALVE IN THE MINI-BULK CABINET WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE STEM. THE SPILLED MATERIAL DRAINED INTO THE CABINET AS THE TRAILER WAS BEING LOAD. AFTER THE TRAILER WAS LOADED, THE DRIVER STARTED TO DRIVE THROUGH THE FACILITY TO LEAVE THE PROPERTY. CAUSTIC SODA STARTED DRIPPING FROM A DRAIN HOLE IN THE CABINET ONTO THE ASPHALT LOT OF THE TERMINAL. THE NUSTAR FACILITY CONTACTED AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WHO PRESSURE WASHED THE AREA AND PUMPED THE RINSE WATER INTO THE FACILITY WASTE WATER TANKS.   THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO DBL TANK SERVICES FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. THE INTERNAL VALVE ON COMPARTMENT #1 WAS REPLACED. AN EXTERNAL VALVE IN THE MINI-BULK CABINET WAS ALSO REPLACED. THREE ADDITIONAL EXTERNAL VALVES WERE REBUILT. THE TANKER WAS THEN HYDROSTATICALLY TESTED AFTER REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETED.
column169: THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH THE DRIVER. DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AND INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THAT THE TRAILER IS FULLY VISUALLY INSPECTED WHICH INCLUDES AND INSPECTION OF THE CABINET WHICH HOUSES THE MINI-BULK PUMP, PIPING AND VALVES TO ENSURE THERE ARE NO LEAKS PRIOR TO TRANSPORT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: BNSF trainyard employees reported a strong odor occurring in the immediate area of GAMX 2526.  BNSF hazmat responders evaluated and found loose manway bolts and a failed manway nozzle gasket.  It was torn and deteriorated and rendered ineffective.  Manway gasket was replaced and manway bolts properly secured.  No liquid spill, no remediation actions, car was allowed to continue in service.    Release quantity was unquantifiable due to being vapor (smell) only as reported by local field personnel.
column169: Evaluate procedures and conduct training as needed to ensure proper inspections and loading/securement techniques are being utilize to prevent NAR's from occurring in the future.

column168: OOLU 924689 was noted as having dried leaking product hanging from the bottom of the container. Upon inspection by a remediation contractor, a drum was noted as having a damaged chime that resulted in the leak.  An estimated 10 gallons of product was released.  The cause was improper bracing and blocking inside of the container.
column169: Shipper needs to ensure that all cargo is properly braced and blocked prior to releasing for shipment to prevent future releases of hazardous materials.

column168: Employee approached a curve and was then coming down a hill. It was cold and drizzling.Employee took his foot off the gas and the engine brake was on, it caused the rear wheels to lock up to slow the truck down. The truck started going sideways and slid across the lanes into the other lane and his front tire caught the edge of the pavement and he rolled over onto his passenger side. He was not injured, no other vehicles were involved.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver hooked up 3" hose from customer tank to a vac tanker.  The customer opened the valve from the tank, but the driver was unable to start the pump on the tanker because it was frozen.  The customer immediately close the valve on the tank and the driver disconnected the hose from the truck and the material from the hose drained into a 5g bucket which accidentally tipped over spilling the contents.  Approximately 6-10g was spilled.  The driver immediately used spill pads to clean up the area.  The pads were placed into a DOT container and the container was sent to the proper disposal facility.  A few days later the spill area was power washed and the residual waste was placed in a drum and that drum was forwarded to the same disposal facility.
column169: Driver was reminded to verify and inspect the equipment during his Pre-trip & Post-trip inspections and to report anything that is not operating properly.  An additional valve was installed on the customer's valve to prevent product leaving the hose in an event of something failing.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Driver attempted to lift a 55g drum using a drum dolly. One of the feet of the drum dolly was bent so the driver was unable to get under the drum properly.  The driver then tilted the drum and a bung wrench underneath the drum so that he could place the drum dolly underneath. As he maneuvered the drum dolly underneath the drum the drum rolled onto the bung wrench and puncture the drum.  With assistance from the Material handler the drum was placed on its side to minimize the amount spilled. The drum was immediately placed into an 85 gallon over-pack and the immediate area was clean up. The overpack and clean up material were sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: The foot on the dolly was replaced and all additional dollies used by the driver's were inspected.

column168: After unloading, driver washed off his connections causing water and product mixture to spill over the curb.
column169: Driver should not have washed his connections off at the consignee.

column62: Inadequate Procedures; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: 29 MARCH 2017, NORTHROP GRUMMAN TECHNOLOGY SERVICES RECEIVED 1 EXPLOSIVE CARTRIDGE, APU FIRE BOTTLE THAT WAS RECEIVED WITH THE FOLLOWING DISCREPANCIES:  1. PACKAGE WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED WITH UN NUMBER, EXPLOSIVE CLASS AND PACKAGING GROUP.   2. APU CARTRIDGE WAS NOT PACKAGED IN AN ANTI-STATIC BAG (INNER PACKAGING) AS REQUIRED.  3. APU CARTRIDGE DID NOT HAVE THE CAP/PLUG INSTALLED AS REQUIRED.     THE CARTRIDGE PART NUMBER IS AE873571, SERIAL NUMBER 394108, WITH A MATERIAL DESCRIPTION OF CARTRIDGE, APU FIRE BOTTLE THAT WAS DROP SHIPPED TO NORTHROP GRUMMAN LAKE CHARLES ON BEHALF OF STATE INDUSTRIAL, BY JETSON AEROSPACE CORP., VIA STANDARD OVERNIGHT THROUGH FED EX, WITHOUT DECLARING AND MARKING THE PACKAGE. THE PART WAS THEN CONTAINED IN THE NG STORAGE BUNKER FOR EXPLOSIVES. PROCUREMENT AND SUPPLIER QUALITY NOTIFIED THE SUPPLIER, STATE INDUSTRIAL OF THE NEAR-MISS INCIDENT AND INFORMED THEM NORTHROP GRUMMAN WOULD PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE CARTRIDGE.   NOTES FROM SECTION 25: AS THIS INCIDENT DID NOT INVOLVE A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, THERE ARE NO APPLICABLE “HOW FAILED"CODES.
column169: THE SUPPLIER IS BEING ISSUED A SUPPLIER CORRECTIVE ACTION REQUEST FOR THEIR FAILURE TO PROPERLY PACKAGE THE ITEM FOR SHIPMENT; FURTHER BUSINESS WITH THE SUPPLIER HAS BEEN SUSPENDED PENDING ACCEPTABLE RESOLUTION OF THE SUPPLIER CORRECTIVE ACTION REQUEST.    AT A MINIMUM; THE SUPPLIER, STATE INDUSTRIAL NEEDS TO PUT IN PLACE MORE ROBUST TRAINING PROGRAMS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPPING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THAT SHIPMENTS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARE PROPERLY MARKED, PACKAGED AND PROCESSED FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: ONE PIECE OF THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED TWO PACKAGE FIBERDRUM SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT THE COLOGNE AIRPORT. IT WAS SEPARATED AND REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND WAS ISOLATED FROM ALL OTHER SHIPMENTS. THE FIBERDRUM WAS NEVER OPENED AND WAS TURNED OVER TO A VENDOR FOR IMMEDIATE DISPOSAL. WE WERE NEVER ABLE TO SEE INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THERE WAS AN ERROR AS THE SPILL WAS NOT REPORTED TO MY DG ADMIN. OFFICE UNTIL THE SPILL REPORT ARRIVED 5 DAYS LATER ON 3-15. BECAUSE OF THIS TIME LAPSE, IT CAUSED MY OFFICE TROUBLES IN TRYING TO RECEIVE INFORMATION ABOUT THE SHIPMENT, AS I WAS TRYING TO WORK WITH MANAGEMENT TEAM IN COLOGNE, AS WELL AS CHINA, AND ALSO IN SWEDEN. I HAD CONTACTED JANET MCLAUGHLIN OF THE DC/FAA AT 16:30 ON 3-22-2017 DUE TO THIS DELAYED NOTIFICATION TO ADVISE HER, AND ALSO THOMAS KENNY OF THIS INCIDENT. THE SECOND PACKAGE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT LEAKING AND HAD MOVED ON TO STOCKHOLM WAS LATER RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE SHIPPER HAS STATED THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT DANGEROUS GOODS, BUT THE MSDS THAT WAS PROVIDED CLEARLY SHOWED THAT IT WAS. THE SHIPPER HAS BEEN SLOW TO RESPOND TO EMAILS REGARDING THIS INCIDENT.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, APPROXIMATELY ONE-GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED ASPHALT UNTIL A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDERNEATH TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL (SWS) WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  SWS ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE SITE. SWS CONFIRMED THAT NO SOIL OR DRAINS WERE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE. SWS DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO RECOVER THE FREE LIQUID. SWS RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. TRACTOR-TANKER WENT OFF THE ROADWAY RESULTING IN DAMAGE TO THE TANKER. AN ESTIMATED 1,500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WERE RELEASED AND IMPACTED SOIL, A RAVINE, AND TWO STORM DRAINS. THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SITE. FIRE DEPARTMENT CONSTRUCTED A DAM AND DEPLOYED ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN AS MUCH FREE LIQUID AS POSSIBLE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL (FEC) WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  FEC RESPONDED AND ASSESSED THE SITE. FEC FOUND SEVERAL LARGE PUDDLES OF STANDING FUEL THAT BEEN CONTAINED AND COVERED WITH FOAM FROM THE FD. A VAC TRUCK WAS IMMEDIATELY REQUESTED TO ASSIST WITH REMOVAL OF STANDING PRODUCT AND DRAIN FLUSHING. THE VAC TRUCK BEGAN REMOVING THE STANDING PRODUCT FROM THE ASPHALT DITCH LINE. DURING THE VACUUMING PROCESS IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE ASPHALT HAD DETERIORATED TO THE POINT OF FAILURE. ONCE CLEANED, FCE BEGAN REMOVING THE SAND USED FOR THE DAMMING PROCESS. FEC FLUSHED THE IMPACTED DRAINS WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT. ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE DEPLOYED AS NEEDED TO RECOVER RESIDUAL FUEL. AT THIS TIME COMPLETION OF SITE EXCAVATION IS PENDING.

column168: Event/Claim # 63967     Driver was hooked up and unloading when his 2" hose ruptured. There was a hole in the hose approximately 2" long..  Driver was only three (3) steps away from the pump so he hit the shut off on the Hydro-Chem Pump and then ran to the back of the trailer to close the internal valve and external valve. At this time the customer noticed him running and shut their receiving end as well. The release lasted less than two (2) minutes..  Customer called clean up crew.  They were then able to unloaded the rest of the product using a new unloading hose.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. LEAK WAS DETECTED COMING FROM BACK OF TRAILER, WHILE STATIONED AT THE EMPIRE EXPRESS YARD. AREA WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER WAS CONSULTED. CHEMOURS RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. CHEMOURS OFFLOADED 11 OF THE 12 FLOBINS INTO A RECOVERY TRAILER PROVIDED BY EMPIRE EXPRESS. ONE FLOBIN WAS DISCOVERED WITH A FAULTY GASKET, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF 1 POUND OF SODIUM CYANIDE TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND GRAVEL SURFACE BENEATH THE TRAILER. CLEAN HARBORS WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. CLEAN HARBORS USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON TRAILER FLOOR AND SHOVELED THE IMPACTED GRAVEL BENEATH. SPENT ABSORBENTS AND CONTAMINATED GRAVEL WERE PLACED INTO ONE 55-GALLON DRUM, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. GASKET WAS TIGHTENED ON THE LEAKING FLOBIN, CONTAINER WAS SHRINK WRAPPED AND SECURED, AND PLACED ONTO TRAILER TO BE RETURNED TO CHEMOURS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: EMPIRE EXPRESS WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE SORT. UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND ONE ROUND METAL CAN WITH A FRICTION LID. THERE WAS NO POSITIVE CLOSURE ON THE FRICTION LID IN VIOLATION OF 49 CFR 173.27 (D). THE SECOND INNER PACKAGING WAS A RECTANGULAR METAL CAN WITH A SCREW ON CAP. THERE WAS NO TAPE ON THE SCREW ON CAP TO PRECLUDE THE CAP FROM THE BACKING OFF DUE TO VIBRATION ON THE AIRCRAFT. THAT IS A VIOLATION OF 49 CFR 173.27 (D). THE THIRD INNER PACKAGING WAS A METAL CYLINDRICAL CONTAINER. THE FIRST TWO INNER WERE 3.78 LITERS AND THE THIRD INNER WAS 946 ML FOR A TOTAL OF 8.506L THE DECLARATION LISTED THE QUANTITY SHIPPER AS 10L. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS NO INSPECTION. HAZMAT MANAGER JOAN HAAS WAS NOTIFIED ELECTRONICALLY.

column42: OXYGEN GENERATOR, CHEMICAL (INCLUDING WHEN CONTAINED IN ASSOCIATED EQUIPMENT, E.G., PASSENGER SERVICE UNITS (PSUS), PORTABLE BREATHING EQUIPMENT (PBE), ETC).
column168: On March 16th 2017 AALA offered a Passenger Service Unit (PSU) containing an oxygen generator for air transportation on FedEx AWB 720035551342 from Tulsa, Oklahoma to Flushing, New York (LGA). The undeclared PSU was accepted and transported on FedEx Cargo without properly being declared for transportation.         All Passenger Service Unit (PSU) panels containing or not containing an oxygen generator, as well as oxygen generators are flagged as hazardous materials in the Inventory system and flagged forbidden for shipment in the American Airlines hazardous materials shipping system  - HazRaps.  As required by American Airlines Policy and Procedures the required yellow caution tag “Caution Contains Oxygen Generator” was on the part as well as the green hazardous materials (HM) sticker on the outside of the non-specification fiberboard box that contained the PSU panel for storage purposes.   Load Center Continued Maintenance Visit (CMV) received an AOG request to pull PSU from stock for shipping to LGA.   TUL Shipping/Receiving picked up the box containing the PSU from CMV and delivered to Tulsa Warehouse Shipping/Receiving for shipment to LGA.   The box containing the PSU was not placed in the designated hazardous materials area in the TUL Warehouse to be sent to TUL Control Materials Storage (CMS) for dangerous goods processing.   The box was placed in the FedEx shipping area and was input in the FedEx shipping system for processing pick-up by FedEx.   It appears the American Airlines employee working the FedEx area did not open the box to verify the part per procedure, nor noticed the green HM sticker on the top of the box, the yellow caution tag inside the box or pull the part up in the Inventory System to see the yellow hazardous materials banner.    Shipping/Receiving does not identify what employees work in a specific area on a given day, so a specific employee could not be identified who was working the FedEx machine on 3/16/2017.
column169: American Airlines Tech Ops Supply/Stores Director provided the below recommendations/actions regarding the oxygen generator shipment.      The result of the AA root cause analysis determined the following causal factors.    · The load center (CMV) described above processed the shipping paperwork (transfer between AA locations).  This shipping paperwork is the finial internal shipping document when the product is within the inventory system and delivered direct from the load center to the shipping dock for processing.      · The aircraft on ground (AOG) desk material logistic specialist (MLS) shipper did not observe the HM label on the exterior of the box or the paperwork internal to the shipping box.  If the MLS would have identified the HM sticker label and paperwork, the box would have been properly labeled and therefore would have been properly shipped.    · The MLS shipper was current on all the training requirements.     Action: Tulsa Stores will implement two additional training days day one will cover “49CFR Haz by Ground  - MX01797” and “IATA Haz by Air  - MX01796”.    Action: Tulsa Stores will provide a designated area within shipping identified for the staging of HAZMAT materials.  The area will be outlined with high visibility tape on the floor

column168: Our tractor unit #GTK018 was hauling cargo tank #GTQ018 loaded with 9,162 gallons of propane. During transit on a sharp curve, the liquid propane load shifted, causing both units to roll to the right. Both units continued to roll and struck a barbed wire fence and a tree before coming to rest on their side in the SB ditch of FM 1447 facing SE. Law enforcement, fire personnel, emergency management and operations personnel arrived at the scene and remained there during the road closure for approximately twelve hours. Dewitt Emergency management claimed a vapor/gas leak from the pressure relief valve on the rear top which may have been possible if the vessel was sideways and the liquid placed pressure on the spring and caused the valve to open a bit to relieve pressure but there is no evidence of this occurrence. DPG personnel arrived three hours later to transfer the propane to their tank #T205. The pressure relief valve was tightened upon their arrival. Once it was 40% offloaded, the wreckers were able to connect to the tank and held it at a better angle to complete the rest of the offloading. Operations personnel found no leaks or damages to the valves during this time. The product was hauled to DPG's yard in Seguin, TX and was stored there for about 4 days. Then, the product was picked up at DPG and a second transfer was done from tank T205 to GIGO's tank #GTK010. The tank was inspected, and there was no damage found to the pressure relief valves, nor bends or cracks in the springs. There is no evidence of a liquid spill and the exact loss of product could not be determined, as it was not weighted after the first transfer. However, based on the weight scale receipt after the second transfer, it is possible the 693 gallons were lost during the transfers and not due to a valve failure.  There was also, a spill of about 25 gallons of motor oil and antifreeze from the engine of the tractor, which was cleaned up by CTI a few days later.  Tank and tractor were towed away. No injuries or fatalities reported.

column168: AT 5:36 HRS ON 3/8/2017/ IT WAS REPORTED THAT A CHLORINE SMELL WAS DETECTED AROUND TWO RESIDUE CHLORINE CARS AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) JACKSON, MS YARD. KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DEPLOYED HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTORS TO INVESTIGATE. RAILCAR AXLX 73533 WAS FOUND TO BE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THE A END LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED COMPLETELY AND RESPONDERS TURNED VALVE HANDLE 3/4 TURN TO FULLY CLOSED POSITION TO STOP LEAK. THE PLUG WAS ALSO REMOVED AND TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE THREADS AND RE-TIGHTENED. THE CREW CHECKED FOR LEAKS AGAIN WITH AN AMMONIA SOLUTION AND NONE WERE LOCATED. A 4 GAS METER WITH A CHLORINE SENSOR READ NON DETECT TO ALSO DETERMINE THE LEAK HAD STOPPED. FILE NOTE: ITEM 19 THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILLING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A "BULK" SHIPMENT AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTITY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASE (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARD, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE BY LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASE (AKA PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSES OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAYS P.O BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: Driver was pumping product into an AST when the fitting ruptured causing a 20 gallon spill. Investigation revealed that driver was transferring product from ETC trailer using company pump and was delivering from a 3 inch pump line into a 1 inch line resulting in the failure of the reduced fitting causing a spill. Product spill was between 25-30 gallons. Action Environmental was contacted to manage the clean up. SWS was sent to the scene. Spill was reported to TEMA.
column169: Driver was instructed to use unauthorized fitting by his manager and regional manager. Both were written up by the VP Operations. Using unauthorized equipment will not be tolerated.

column168: The consignee was unloading the CTMV and noticed hazardous material leaking from the external valve stem at the stuffing box nut. column168: Driver loaded crude oil at a lease on Exxon road, departed and stopped at the intersection of Exxon road and FM 1314. Driver proceeded to turn onto FM 1314 and noticed product had sloshed out of the top of the cargo tank onto the roadway in the intersection. Local police and fire department were called and closed the roadway. An emergency response team was also called to clean up the oil spill from the roadway and edge of the road.  The cargo tank had been washed out and repair work completed on it by a third party vendor and had been released back into service with the washout caps left off and dome lid not secured. When the driver stopped at the intersection, the product sloshed out of these openings.  An area approximately 4' x 20' x 18" of contaminated soil was excavated and removed for disposal. Excavation was refilled with new soil. The trailer was cleaned up, caps and dome lid secured.
column169: Proper procedures were reviewed with the vendor on closing and securing washout caps and closures after wash out and repairs are completed. Communication and verification processes were emphasized to prevent cargo tank trailers being put back into service prior to them being inspected and verified that all closures are secured.

column168: 2:30 PM – PEROXYCHEM DRIVER ESCORTED TWO CONTRACT PERSONNEL TO THE KINGFISHER, OK HOSPITAL ER. THE CONTRACT PERSONNEL HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY EXPOSED TO PERACETIC ACID AT THE OKARCHE, OK DELIVERY LOCATION. THE CONTRACT PERSONNEL WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.     3:10 PM – THE TOTE ON THE DELIVERY TRUCK PRESSURIZED AND BLEW OUT THE BOTTOM OF TOTE. THE OVER PRESSURIZATION WAS DUE TO DECOMPOSING PRODUCT IN THE HEEL OF THE TOTE THAT GENERATED EXOTHERMIC HEAT DEGRADING THE TOTE BOTTOM. THE DECOMPOSING PRODUCT WAS CAUSED BY A BACK FLOW OF CONTAMINATION INTO THE TOTE AFTER THE TOTE HAD BEEN EMPTIED. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WAS CONTACTED BY THE PEROXYCHEM DRIVER. ABOUT 0.5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE TRUCK BED AND GROUND.     3:15 PM – EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ARRIVED TO HOSPITAL PARKING LOT.    3:16 PM - SDS WAS PROVIDED TO TONY STEWART, FIRE CHIEF, KINGFISHER, OK AND PEROXYCHEM PERSONNEL REVIEWED THE CHEMICAL COMPOSITION AND PROPER TREATMENT OF THE SPILL.     3:20 PM – FIRE PERSONNEL BEGAN RINSING HOSPITAL PAVEMENT.
column169: 1. PEROXYCHEM O & G WILL NO LONGER DO A “DROP” TO A SITE LOCATION THAT WILL UNLOAD FROM PEROXYCHEM’S TRUCK INTO 3RD PARTY EQUIPMENT. PEROXYCHEM WILL ONLY DELIVER OUR PRODUCTS TO A CUSTOMER’S WAREHOUSE.     2.  ALL PUMPING WILL BE PERFORMED FROM PEROXYCHEM’S TRUCK/TOTES DIRECTLY THROUGH PEROXYCHEM’S PUMP AND EQUIPMENT.
