column168: DRIVER HAD ATTEMPTED TO MAKE DELIVERY OF FUEL OIL TO RESIDENCE ON PRIOR DAY AND FOUND THE POSITION OF THE STORAGE TANK AT RESIDENCE WAS TO REAR OF THE HOUSE, WHICH IS LOCATED IN A VERY DEEP FRONTAGE LOT, AND DETERMINED THE UNIT HE WAS DRIVING DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT DELIVERY HOSE ON PUMP REEL TO REACH THE TANK FROM THE POSITION THE DELIVERY TRUCK HAD TO BE PARKED. DRIVER RETURNED NEXT DAY, ON DAY OF INCIDENT, WITH ANOTHER DELIVERY TRUCK UNIT THAT HAD A 50’ LONGER DELIVERY HOSE ON THE HOSE REEL; OR A TOTAL OF 150 COILED DELIVERY HOSE ON REEL. DRIVER POSITIONED UNIT, UNCOILED THE 150’ LENGTH OF DELIVERY HOSE FROM REEL IN ORDER TO REACH THE TANK. CONNECTION WAS MADE WITH DELIVERY NOZZLE FROM DELIVERY HOSE INTO TOP FILL PORT OF RECEIVING TANK.     DRIVER INITIATED ACTIVATION OF TRUCK PUMPING SYSTEM TO EFFECT FUEL DELIVERY AND WAS RETURNING TO A POSITION HEAR THE RECEIVING FUEL OIL TANK WHEN HE OBSERVED FUEL OIL PRODUCT SPRAYING OUT THE END OF THE DELIVERY HOSE THAT CONNECTED TO THE TRUCK REEL/PUMPING MECHANISM. DRIVER RETURNED TO THE REAR OF HIS UNIT AND SHUT DOWN THE TRUCK PUMP TO STOP THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS. THE TRUCK PUMP METER REFLECTED THAT 49.5 GALLONS HAD BEEN DISCHARGED THROUGH THE PUMP AND AS SUCH THIS IS THE GALLON AMOUNT WE CONTRIBUTED TO THE MAX TOTAL THAT COULD HAVE BEEN SPILLED. DRIVER POSITIONED ABSORBENT MATERIALS HE HAD ON TRUCK IN POSITION AND THEN EFFECTED CALL INTO OUR OPERATIONS GROUP. CALL WAS MADE TO LOCAL 911 WHICH RESULTED IN MIAMI TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDING TO SITE TO CONTAIN THE AREA. WE PLACED NOTIFICATION CALLS TO NRC, OHEPA. AND CLERMONT COUNTY LEPC AS WELL.     AS LOCATION WAS VERY CLOSE TO OUR CORPORATE OFFICE; TWO SAFETY DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO SITE. UPON ARRIVAL AT SITE, MIAMI TWP. F.D. HAD PLACED APPROPRIATE ABSORBENT MATERIALS IN PLACE AND THE MIGRATION OF THE FUEL OIL IN THE DITCH AREA CONTAINED TO A 20’ LENGTH AREA IN DITCH-LINE. A METAL CULVERT PIPE WAS POSITIONED UNDER THE RESIDENCE DRIVEWAY AND FED OUT SEVERAL FEET INTO DITCH-LINE AND FREE PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED ON THE OUTSIDE PARAMETER OF THE PIPE ALONG GROUND LEVEL. WE DETERMINED THE NEED TO ADDRESS EXCAVATION ALONG AND UNDER THE METAL CULVERT PIPE IN THE DITCH-LINE IN ORDER TO PROPERLY RE-MEDIATE THE SPILLAGE AND WE RETAINED SUPERIOR ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTIONS (SES) TO RESPOND FOR FURTHER SITE RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES. SES WAS ONSITE WITHIN TWO HOURS AND INITIATED ADDITIONAL INITIAL RESPONSE AND WAS ABLE OVER A COUPLE OF DAYS COMPLETE THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE TO ACCEPTABLE STANDARDS.     INSPECTION AT SITE AND FOLLOW-UP INSPECTION OF THE TRUCK DELIVERY UNIT AT OUR REPAIR FACILITY REFLECTED THAT THE DRIVER HAD UN-COILED THE ENTIRE 150 FOOT OF DELIVERY HOSE FROM TRUCK PUMP HOSE REEL AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE HOSE END ATTACHED TO THE HOSE REEL FAILED. THE RUBBER END OF HOSE IS WEDGED INTO THE SLEEVE WITH A FERRULE, IT WAS AT THIS POINT THAT THE HOSE CAME UNCOUPLED AND LET THE PRODUCT ESCAPE. REPAIR TO OUR UNIT INCLUDED REPLACEMENT
column169: THE COMPANY REVIEWS ALL INCIDENTS TO DETERMINE CAUSATION AND ADDRESS IF THE INCIDENTS WERE PREVENTABLE OR NON-PREVENTABLE. IN THIS INCIDENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO AREAS OF CONCERN WERE NOTED. ONE, THE INTEGRITY OF THE AREA OF THE PRODUCT HOSE WHERE THE HOSE IS CONNECTED TO THE PUMP REEL AND THE RUBBER HOSE WEDGED INTO THE SLEEVE WITH A FERRULE. THE OTHER WAS THE CONTRIBUTORY ACTION OF THE DRIVER UN-COILING THE ENTIRE LENGTH OF THE DELIVERY HOSE FROM THE DELIVERY HOSE REEL OF THE TRUCK UNIT.   AS TO THE FIRST; INSPECTION OF THE COMPONENTS DID NOT SHOW ANY EXCESS WEAR, CORROSION OR ALIKE THAT WOULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE SITUATION, NOR WERE THERE SIGNS OF ANY PRIOR LEAKAGE AT THE CONNECTION AREA OF THE HOSE TO THE REEL. DISCUSSION WAS HELD WITH OUR MAINTENANCE GROUP AS TO THE NEED TO MAKE SURE THAT ALL PROPER PROCEDURES ARE UTILIZED DURING THE INSTALLATION – CLAMPING/TIGHTENING ASPECTS WHEN REPLACING A DELIVERY HOSE ON THE REEL MECHANISM.     AS TO THE SECOND; DISCUSSION HELD WITH DRIVER AS TO PROPER DELIVERY PROCEDURES AND THE NEED TO MINIMIZE THE PULLING OF THE DELIVERY HOSE AND PROCEDURE TO NOT COMPLETELY UNCOIL THE HOSE ON THE REEL DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS.  ALL DRIVERS RECEIVE TRAINING IN PROPER PROCEDURAL PERFORMANCE OF ALL JOB FUNCTIONS INCLUDING THOSE ASSOCIATED TO THE DELIVERY PROCESS. WE HOLD QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETINGS WITH OPERATIONAL, MAINTENANCE AND DRIVER STAFFS TO REVIEW SUCH AREAS AS MECHANICAL ISSUES, LOADING ISSUES, TRANSPORTATION ISSUED, DELIVERY ISSUES AND ALIKE AND HOW BEST PRACTICES CAN BE USED TO AVOID THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT. ALL WILL BE BRIEFED ON THIS INCIDENT IN AN UPCOMING SAFETY MEETING AND AS PART OF OUR ON-GOING TRAINING PROGRAMS.

column168: Employee states that he drifted onto the shoulder of the road and the front wheel caught the grass and he tried to correct and went off the passenger side of the roadway. The bobtail leaked about 5 gallons. Damages were to the cab and the passenger side was crushed bottle is dented. No other vehicles were involved. No other property damage.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate.

column14: Approx 9 mi WSW of Lovelady TX
column60: Failed to Operate; Failed to Operate
column168: On Thursday, March 30 two RSI field employees (Mike Ward - Delivery Driver and Will Bathe - Field Tech) had completed flushing of chemical transfer hoses with RSI-101, an oilfield chemical product containing xylene and other hydrocarbon solvents, as well as minor amounts of cresylic acid, at a well site operated by Interstate Exploration LLC (Gore - Oil Lease #027135) approximately 9 miles southwest of Lovelady, Houston County, Texas. The employees departed the location and traveled in separate vehicles from the lease site along FM 2915, before turning southwest onto FM 230 and shortly afterward, onto County Road 3495. Mr. Bathe was in the lead vehicle and arrived at the next lease site (C.T. Adams - Oil Lease #026715) first and proceeded to the service location (C.T. Adams #2, operated by Layline Petroleum LLC). The lease gate had been left open because the pumper was on-site gauging tanks. As the RSI delivery driver approached, Mr. Bathe observed that the chemical transfer hose had become disconnected from the transfer pump and that chemical appeared to be flowing from it. He quickly ran over to the tote of RSI-101 on the bed of the delivery vehicle and immediately closed the valve, which had been left open by the driver, Mr. Ward. Approximately 125 gallons of chemical had spilled along several hundred linear feet of lease road and a small portion of CR 3495, creating an impacted area of 5-600' long by 1' wide (max) and no more than 1/4" deep.  The duration of the spill was anywhere from half a minute to a minute, and appeared to have started approximately 60' in advance of the lease entrance on CR 3495. No traffic was present at the time and no individuals were injured or impacted by the spill, nor were any waterways or inland water bodies affected. The spill site is located in a predominantly rural and sparsely populated area which is also used for cattle grazing; no residences were observed on the lease property and grazing cattle did not come into contact with the spilled product. After surveying the nature and extent of the spill, Mr. Bathe proceeded to contact his supervisor (Terry Johnson) and the RSI Health and Safety Manager (Robert Menser), followed by the contract pumper (Keith Krenek), who notified the lease operator. The RSI Health and Safety Manager contacted the RSI Environmental Manager (Karl Mueller) at 0948 hours on March 30, and an emergency response/remediation contractor (Cleaning Solutions, Inc of Bryan, Texas) was dispatched to the site to perform clean-up activities. Two Cleaning Solutions personnel arrived at the site at around 1330 to begin the initial response, which consisted of absorbing and removing any remaining free product using a cellulose-based product (Sphag Sorb). Two 55-gallon drums of spent sorbent materials were generated as a result of this activity. The crew then used a trailer-mounted pressure washer and water tank to apply a water-based solution of Micro Blaze - a blend of nutrients, wetting agents, a
column169: The direct cause of the incident was the use of an old O-ring gasket which prevented a secure seal between the hose connector and pump fitting and allowed the hose to be jarred loose while in transit. Contributing factors were inadequate pre-trip planning because the truck was not supplied with any spare gaskets. The incident root cause was due to two separate violations of internal company policy and DOT regulations. Leaving a hose connected to an IBC is not allowed due to the extra weight and stresses placed on the valve, which could cause it to fail by compromising its physical integrity.  In addition, however, the valve was left open, which resulted in a spill when the hose became disconnected. An "HSE Alert" bulletin describing the incident and the policy/procedure violations which were the root cause will be sent out to field staff, along with the clear instruction that travel with hoses connected is prohibited, regardless of how short the travel distance might be.

column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT.WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELLING EAST ON I-265 IN SLOWING TRAFFIC. OUR DRIVER STATED HE DIDN'T SEE THE "SLOWING TRAFFIC" HAD STOPPED. WHEN HE SAW STOPPED VEHICLES HE APPLIED HARD BRAKES AND STEERED TO THE RIGHT. THE SUDDEN BRAKE AND HARD STEER CAUSED A LOAD TO SHIFT REQUIRING A COUNTER STEER TO THE LEFT, THIS MANEUVER POSITIONED THE TRUCK TO STRIKE VEH #2. THE COUNTER STEER AND LOAD SURGE CAUSE THE TRUCK TO ROLL OVER, PUNCTURING THE TANK VEHICLE IN TWO SPOTS LEAKING 3185 GALLONS INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE PUNCTURES WERE PLUGGED AND A SECOND UNIT FROM SERVICE TRANSPORT LLC WAS DISPATCHED TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING GALLONS ON THE ROLLED TANK. 5278 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED. SOUTHERN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND BEGAN TO CONTROL-COLLECT CONTAMINATES AT THE SCENE. THE SAME COMPANY IS EXECUTING A RE-MEDIATION PLAN TO CLEAN-UP THE AFFECTED AREA.
column169: WE RETAINED THIS DRIVER, UNTIL THIS ACCIDENT HE HAD NEVER MADE A MISTAKE. A WEEK AFTER THE ACCIDENT HE MET WITH THE SAFETY DIRECTOR FOR TWO DAYS TO DO AN ANALYSIS OF THE ACCIDENT, THAT INCLUDED A REVISIT TO THE SCENE. WE REVIEWED AND TESTED DEFENSIVE DRIVING KNOWLEDGE AND HE WAS TESTED IN THE DRIVER PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS SYSTEM (DPAS). HE SCORED ABOVE AVERAGE IN 3 OF THE 4 CATEGORIES AND AVERAGE IN ONE. HIS LOWER SCORE WAS TRAFFIC PERCEPTIONS". LATER WE TRAINED IN CAB, (DRIVER AND SAFETY DIRECTOR) WORKING ON DEFENSIVE SKILLS (KEYS) AND SIGHT SKILLS. A ROAD TEST WAS DOCUMENTED AT THE END AND HE WAS RELEASED TO DRIVE ON HIS OWN.

column168: DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, THE GASKET CAM UNGLUED FROM THE DOME COVER AND FELL OFF THE RIM OF THE COVER. THE OPERATOR LOADING THE TRAILER DID NOT NOTICE THAT THE GASKET CAME OFF AND LODGED IN THE CRASH BOX. WHEN THE LOADING WAS COMPLETED, THE COVER WAS CLOSED WITHOUT THE GASKET IN PLACE. THE MISSING GASKET ALLOWED SULFURIC ACID TO LEAK OUT OF THE TRAILER INTO THE CRASH BOX AND DOWN THE DRAIN TUBE. ACID WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER WHILE THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED AT THE SECURITY GUARD STATION AT THE DESTINATION IN MIDDLE TOWN.
column169: THE GASKET WAS REGLUED INTO PLACE UNDER THE DOME COVER BY A CONTRACTOR WHO SPECIALIZES IN TRAILER MAINTENANCE AND REPAIR. OCCASIONALLY THE GASKET COMES UNGLUED ON THE FIBERGLASS REINFORCED PLASTIC TRAILERS. UNIVAR WILL REVIEW LOADING PROCEDURES WITH ALL YARD SPECIALISTS AND DRIVERS TO REINFORCE THE IMPORTANCE OF VERIFYING THE DOME COVER GASKET IS IN PLACE PRIOR TO MOVING THE TRAILER

column62: Human Error; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT 2ND STOP OF A MULTIPLE STOP RUN AND AFTER OPENING TRAILER DOORS, HAZMAT DRIVER DISCOVERED A DRUM OF CYANIDE THAT HAD SLID OFF PALLET IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER AND ROLLED TO MID TRAILER, LANDING ON ITS SIDE AGAINST THE WALL. LESS THAN ONE CUP OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. THE CUSTOMER AND NOR OUR DRIVER WERE EQUIPPED TO HANDLE RECTIFYING THIS SITUATION AND SHAMROCK ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM WHO WAS LOCATED ACROSS THE STREET WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND. THE DRUM WAS UP-RIGHTED AND WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BUNG BECAME LOOSE FROM ROLLING SIDE TO SIDE AND BANGING AGAINST THE WALLS INSIDE THE TRAILER. THE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED, NO DEFICIENCIES WERE FOUND ON THE DRUM, AND IT WAS RE-POSITIONED WITH THE OTHER 2 DRUMS ON THE PALLET ON TRAILER AND STRAPPED TO THE WALL.THE INCIDENT OCCURRED DUE TO DRIVER NOT PROPERTY SECURING THE DRUM ON THE PALLET. THE PALLET SHOULD HAVE BEEN STRAPPED TO THE WALL VS. STAGED IN MIDDLE WITH ONE STRAP ACROSS ALL 3 DRUMS.
column169: DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON HOW TO PROPERTY SECURE DRUMS WHEN THERE ARE NOT ANY OTHER CONTAINERS ON BOARD TO BLOCK AND BRACE EACH OTHER.

column168: UN 1789 HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION ON A 3 COMPARTMENT DOT 412 TRANSPORT TRAILER, OUR UNIT 3 2STF24635, AWAITING TRANSFER TO ANOTHER TRAILER BECAUSE OF AN EXPIRED DOT INSPECTION. TRANSPORT UNIT WAS PARKED INSIDE A CONTAINMENT AREA OF OUR FACILITY.     THE VALVE ON THE REAR 850 GAL. COMPARTMENT FAILED AND STARTED LEAKING INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE HSE DEPT. IMPLEMENTED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN AND CONTACTED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROVIDER. DURING THIS TIME OUR HSE RESPONSE TEAM SPREAD SODA ASH ON THE SPILL IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA TO CONTROL FUMES, AND BOLSTERED THE CONTAINMENT WALLS. WHILE WAITING FOR THE ERP TO ARRIVE, THE VALVE ON THE MIDDLE 750 GAL. COMPARTMENT STARTED LEAKING AS WELL.     THE CONTAINMENT AREA CONTAINED ALL OF THE RELEASE AND PREVENTED ANY CONTAMINATION OF THE GROUND OR SURROUNDING AREA. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN WAS IMPLEMENTED AND THE ERP ARRIVED AND TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA INTO IBC’S AND CLEANED THE CONTAINMENT AREA. PH LEVEL TESTING ON ALL THE AREA SURROUNDING THE CONTAINMENT AREA WERE TESTED AND RESULTED IN A PH7.     CLEAN HARBORS WAS BROUGHT IN TO CLEAN AND PURGE THE CTMV BEFORE TRANSPORTING TO POLAR TANK FOR TANK INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 6:01 AM MARCH 09, 2017 OUR FUEL TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON I-15 INTERSTATE. APPROXIMATELY 20 MILES NORTH OF GREAT FALLS THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A SNOW PLOWING HIGH BLADING. THE SNOW BEING STIRRED UP CAUSED OUR DRIVER TO LOSE SIGHT OF THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER WAS PASSING THE SNOW PLOW LEFT THE ROADWAY WHICH CAUSED THE TRAILERS AND TRACTOR TO ROLL. THE IMPACT CAUSED A CRACK IN THE COMPARTMENT OF THE LEAD TRAILER CARRYING GASOLINE. THE CRACK WAS AT THE TOP LEFT SIDE NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.   THE GASOLINE FUEL SPILLED ON THE MEDIAN OF THE INTERSTATE. THE HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM FROM THE CALUMET REFINERY WAS DISPATCHED FOR IMMEDIATE CONTAINMENT. THE LEAK ABOUT ONE AND A HALF HOURS. THE CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY MRTE.   THE TRAILER WAS CARRYING 8000 GALLONS. ALL GALLONS SPILLED. 1956 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED.
column169: WEATHER CONDITIONS WAS DETERMINED AS THE FACTOR CAUSING THE INCIDENT.  EACH DRIVER IS CURRENTLY GIVEN A ROAD TEST BY A QUALIFIED DRIVER TRAINER TO ENSURE THE NEW DRIVER IS CHECKED OFF TO DRIVE SOLO. ADDITIONALLY, EACH DRIVER IS TESTED ON SAFETY VIDEOS TO INCLUDE TRANSPORT ROLL OVER.   CONTINUED EFFORT AND TRAINING WILL BE DONE FOR CURRENT AND FUTURE DRIVERS TO ENSURE THEY UNDERSTAND THE FACTORS OF VEHICLE ROLL-OVER.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: THE DRIVER WAS ON HIS WAY BACK TO THE OFFICE AFTER MAKING A DELIVERY WHEN A HUGE SNOW STORM CAME IN AND DROPPED 3 INCHES OF SNOW IN ABOUT 10 MINUTES. THE ROAD TURNED TO SOLID ICE. HE CAME AROUND A CORNER AND THE BACK OF THE TRUCK SLIDE OUT AND HE TRIED TO CORRECT AND THE TRUCK SLIDE OUT BACK AND HIT THE BACK AND TIPPED ON IT’S SIDE. THE TRUCK SLIDE OFF THE ROAD AND REST OFF THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. FIRE AND POLICE WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE. THE HOSE REEL HIT THE FILL LINE CAUSING A LEAK FROM THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE. EMS AND MYSELF DECIDED IT WOULD BE SAFEST TO BLEED OF THE REMAINING FUEL BEFORE WE TURNED THE TRUCK BACK ON IT TIRES. WE THEN BLEED THE TRUCK OFF AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO OUR SECURE FACILITY.
column169: WE TRAIN ALL DRIVERS ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING & ROAD CONDITIONS. WE ALSO PROVIDE HAZMAT TRAINING WE ALSO PROVIDE CETP TRAIN FOR ALL OF OUR DRIVERS.

column168: THE TRAILER TIRES OF THE TANKER RAN OFF THE ROAD CAUSING THE TRUCK AND TANKER TRAILER TO OVERTURN. WE ALSO CONTACTED CENTERAL EAST SERVICES IN WHICH THEY PROVIDE A VACUUM TRUCK ON SITE, AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRUCK & TRAILER.
column169: WE HAVE MADE ALL OUR EMPLOYEES WATCH A DVD ON TANKER ROLLOVERS “THE POINT OF NO RETURN”.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE BROWARD SHERRIFFS OFFICE ACCIDENT REPORT:     ON MARCH 2, 2017, AT APPROXIMATELY 2325 HOURS, I WAS DISPATCHED TO THE 3200 BLOCK OF S.E. 19TH AVENUE (PORT EVERGLADES) IN REFERENCE TO A FUEL CARRIER ROLLOVER. UPON ARRIVAL, I NOTICED THAT A TRUCK WAS OVERTURNED AND SURROUNDED BY FUEL IN THE LEFT SOUTHBOUND LANE. BACK UP UNITS RESPONDED ON SCENE AND ASSISTED WITH MAINTAINING A PERIMETER AROUND THE INCIDENT TO PREVENT ANY TRAFFIC FROM ENTERING THE CRASH SCENE.  I WAS INFORMED BY BROWARD COUNTY SHERIFF’S OFFICE FIRE RESCUE THAT THE SOLE DRIVER, WHO LATER BECAME KNOWN TO ME AS, JEAN NICOLAS WAS TRANSPORTED TO BROWARD HEALTH MEDICAL CENTER FOR A MINOR LACERATION TO HIS LEFT EYELID AND CHEEK.     I RESPONDED TO BROWARD HEALTH MEDICAL CENTER IN REFERENCE TO INTERVIEWING NICOLAS CONCERNING THIS ACCIDENT. HE SAID “I WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 15 MPH IN THE LEFT LANE.
